"We propose a compact coprocessor for the AES (encryption, decryption, and key expansion) and the cryptographic hash function ECHO on Virtex-5 and Virtex-6 FPGAs. Our architecture is built around an 8-bit datapath. The Arithmetic and Logic Unit performs a single instruction that allows for implementing AES encryption, AES decryption, AES key expansion, and ECHO at all levels of security. Thanks to a careful organization of AES and ECHO internal states in the register file, we manage to generate all read and write addresses by means of a modulo-16 counter and a modulo-256 counter. A fully autonomous implementation of ECHO and AES on a Virtex-5 FPGA requires 193 slices and a single 36k memory block, and achieves competitive throughputs. Assuming that the security guarantees of ECHO are at least as good as the ones of the SHA-3 finalists BLAKE and Keccak, our results show that ECHO is a better candidate for low-area cryptographic coprocessors. Furthermore, the design strategy described in this work can be applied to combine the AES and the SHA-3 finalist Grostl."
